/*
The jquery.scrolly plugin (v1.0.0-dev) enables smooth scrolling for anchor links on a page. It is useful for single-page websites or sections where smooth scroll effects enhance navigation and user experience by animating the scroll position to a specific element when an anchor link is clicked.

How It Works
This plugin listens for a click event on anchor links and, when triggered, calculates the target scroll position based on the provided options. It then animates the scroll to that position, applying easing and offset as specified.

Code Breakdown
Helper Function - u(s, o):

Determines the target scroll position for the element specified by the href attribute (i.e., the anchor link).
Parameters:
s: The anchor link’s selector (e.g., "#section1").
o: Options for adjusting the target position, such as anchor type and offset.
Calculations:
Uses jQuery’s offset method to get the target element’s top position (a).
Calculates f based on the anchor option:
"middle": Centers the target element in the viewport.
"top" (default): Aligns the top of the target element with the top of the viewport.
Adjusts f by subtracting the specified offset to fine-tune the scroll position.
Returns the calculated scroll position (f).
Main Function - scrolly:

Extends jQuery to allow calling scrolly directly on a jQuery element (e.g., $(selector).scrolly(options)).
Parameters:
i: Options object, which defines the scroll behavior.
Default Options:
anchor: Specifies where the element should appear in the viewport when scrolled ("top" or "middle").
easing: Type of animation easing (default: "swing").
offset: Number of pixels to offset the scroll position.
parent: The element to apply the scroll effect to, usually $("body, html").
pollOnce: If true, calculates the target position once, which is useful for static pages where content doesn’t change.
speed: Animation duration in milliseconds (default: 1000 ms).
Event Listener - click.scrolly:

Attaches a click event listener to each element that calls scrolly.
When an anchor link is clicked:
Checks the href attribute to ensure it’s an internal link (starts with #).
Uses the helper function u to calculate the target scroll position.
Animates the scrollTop property of the parent element to smoothly scroll to the target position.
If pollOnce is enabled, it only calculates the position once and reuses it, improving performance for static pages.

// Apply Scrolly to all anchor links
$('a.scrolly').scrolly({
    anchor: 'middle',         // Centers the target element in the viewport
    easing: 'swing',          // Uses swing easing for the animation
    offset: 20,               // Scrolls to 20 pixels above the target
    speed: 1500               // Duration of the scroll animation in milliseconds
});

This setup would apply smooth scrolling to any anchor link with the class scrolly. Clicking the link would scroll the page smoothly to the linked section, positioning it in the middle of the viewport with a 20-pixel offset.

Key Benefits
Smooth Navigation: Enables animated scrolling, which is often more visually appealing and can help users keep track of their position on the page.
Customizable Positioning: Allows alignment of the target element at the top or center of the viewport, as well as an offset to adjust the final scroll position.
Configurable Speed and Easing: Control the duration and easing type of the scroll animation for customized effects.
Summary
jquery.scrolly is a straightforward and flexible plugin for adding smooth scrolling functionality to anchor links on a page. This is particularly useful for one-page websites or navigation within a long page, enhancing the user experience with customizable animation options and precise scroll positioning.
*/